<figureCitation box="[580,707,1988,2014]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetId="figure-101@19.[151,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="170">Figs 81, 82</figureCitation>
) with a smooth subtriangular area corresponding to anterior ocellus, and remains with dense and coarse punctures; POD: OOD=1 (
<figureCitation box="[903,988,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetId="figure-101@19.[151,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
); pronotal (
<figureCitation box="[1119,1201,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetId="figure-101@19.[151,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
) carina degenerated; dorsal surface of propodeum (
<figureCitation box="[483,563,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetId="figure-101@19.[151,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
) densely reticulo-punctate, dorsum without clear boundary between horizontal and posterior surface; metasoma without light spots, and with minute and sparse punctures; each of T1–T6 subapically with a row of punctures and medially absent forming incomplete groove; T7 (
<figureCitation box="[1100,1182,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–85" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetId="figure-101@19.[151,1436,345,1418]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 80–85. Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
) densely punctate and medially smooth and impunctate; apex of T7 with a U-shaped notch, and tipped lobes pointed.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641348" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6641348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641348/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="171" startId="19.[151,264,1441,1465]" targetBox="[153,1436,345,1418]" targetPageId="19">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1441,1501]" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,342,1441,1465]" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">FIGURES 80–85.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Guiglia" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[350,691,1441,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Poecilotiphia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="brevicauda" subSpecies="kaszabi">
<emphasis box="[350,691,1441,1465]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Poecilotiphia brevicauda kaszabi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, ♂. 80. Habitus, dorsal view; 81. Head, frontal view; 82. Vertex, dorsal view; 83. Pronotum, dorsal view; 84. Propodeum, dorsal view; 85. T7, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1547,1790]" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">
Female. Head 1.2× wider than high; width of pronotum 1.3× its length; width of propodeum 1.4× its length, dorsum without distinctly horizontal and vertical surface; dorsum of propodeum medially with sparse punctures, punctures on lateral side denser than those on dorsum; L 
<subScript attach="left" box="[801,833,1638,1652]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Tap5</subScript>
/ L 
<subScript attach="left" box="[865,898,1638,1652]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="171">Tap4</subScript>
about 1.2; metasomal tergum with very sparse (PIS 3–6× Pd) and minute punctures; each of T1–T4 subapically with a row of punctures and medially absent forming incomplete groove; T5–T6 without subapical groove. No female specimens were collected in our study, so the description is referring to 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorbatovsky, V. V." box="[442,671,1727,1754]" pageId="19" pageNumber="171" pagination="309 - 333" refId="ref15830" refString="Gorbatovsky, V. V. (1980) Myzininae from the Mongolian People's Republic and adjacent regions of the USSR and China. Nasekomye Mongolii, 7, 309 - 333. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1980">Gorbatovsky (1980)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
